1 olive oil
1 carrot
2 clove garlic
20 g butter
¾ cup water
1 sachet Chicken-Style Stock Powder
1 packet couscous
½ packet Currants
1 tomato
1 bag baby spinach leaves
½ lemon
1 packet Greek-Style Yoghurt
1 packet beef mince
1 sachet chermoula spice blend
1 egg
1 sachet fine breadcrumbs
½ tsp salt
1 packet flaked almonds

Grate the carrot. Finely chop the garlic. In
a medium saucepan, melt the butter over a
medium-high heat. Cook the carrot, stirring,
until softened, 2-3 minutes. Add 1/2 the garlic
and cook, stirring, until fragrant, 1 minute. Add
the water and chicken-style stock powder and
bring to the boil. Add the couscous, currants (see
ingredients) and a drizzle of olive oil and stir to
combine. Cover with a lid and remove from the
heat. Set aside until all the water is absorbed,
5 minutes. Fluff up with a fork.

While the couscous is cooking, finely chop the
tomato. Roughly chop the baby spinach leaves.
Slice the lemon into wedges. In a small bowl,
combine the Greek-style yoghurt and a squeeze
of lemon juice. Season with salt and pepper.
Set aside.

In a large bowl, combine the beef mince,
chermoula spice blend, egg, fine breadcrumbs
(see ingredients), the salt and remaining garlic.
Season with pepper. Using damp hands, roll the
beef mixture into koftas, then transfer to a plate.
You should get 3-4 koftas per person.

Heat a large frying pan over a medium-high heat.
Toast the flaked almonds, tossing, until golden,
2-3 minutes. Transfer to a bowl. Return the frying
pan to a medium-high heat with a drizzle of olive
oil. Cook the koftas, turning, until browned and
cooked through, 10-12 minutes.

TIP: The koftas are cooked through when they are
no longer pink inside.

While the koftas are cooking, add the tomato and
baby spinach to the cooked couscous and stir
to combine. Add a squeeze of lemon juice, then
season to taste.

Divide the couscous tabbouleh between bowls and
top with the beef koftas. Drizzle over the lemon
yoghurt. Garnish with toasted almonds. Serve with
any remaining lemon wedges.